><p>Tracking trends in construction injuries is harder, due to data consistency issues. A death is a death, but what sort of injury counts as “severe,” or “disabling,” or is even worth reporting is likely to change over time. [3] But we seem to see a similar trend there. Looking at BLS <a href="https://www.bls.gov/iif/data.htm" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Occupational Injuries and Illnesses</a> data, between the 1970s and 2020s the injury rate per 100 workers declined from 15 to 2.5.</p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6df97af0-ce38-4f3f-9896-6722bd880dca_562x399.png" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/DnmWwe8AzYv_ 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/krykMspD_ELa90OHYOgM6zd_ 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/kSKatdT901v0O9a5_Ub1BCVrDI20MsSU_WthmAwAw7g=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xMjcyLGNfbGltaXQsZl93ZWJwLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGNmRmOTdhZjAtY2UzOC00ZjNmLTk4OTYtNjcyMmJkODgwZGNhXzU2MngzOTkucG5n 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/Or- 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux." width="562" height="399" alt="" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/3Hrz5vdFER1yNwNFI_ 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/KQ9BRW5oWfyo_ 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/yPESB6suCbdMTTaN_ 1272w, https://reader.miniflux. 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a><figcaption>Source: BLS IIF data</figcaption></figure><p>Less obviously dangerous fields of construction exhibit a similar trend. Homebuilding, for instance, seems like it would be on the safer end of construction work: less work being done at dangerous heights, fewer